subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis:
The males of this species can be easily identified by the completely black metasomal terga, without yellow maculations and posterior terga with long and dense fox-reddish hair (
Fig. 16h
); while the females may be identified by mostly black pubescence on T1–T3 contrasting with the fox-red pubescence on T4–T6 (
Fig. 15a
) and lower part of face with long black pubescence (
Fig. 15b
). There is some variability in the extent of reddish pubescence in males (
Figs 16f
, 
17e
).

Description:
Female. BL = 7.8 mm (
Fig. 15a
); head broader than long, HW: HL = 60: 54 (
Fig. 15b
); gena slightly broader than eye, GW: EW = 17: 14. Clypeus broader than long, apical margin of clypeus straight and smooth, with two distinctly lateral tubercles (
Fig. 15c
); mandible with six sharp teeth separated by acute notches, the apical one longest (
Fig. 15c
); omaular carina absent; pronotal lobe rounded anteriorly; scutellum rounded posterolaterally, without tooth, not greatly overhanging metanotum and propodeum (
Fig. 15d
); propodeum without fovea behind spiracle; fore wing with two submarginal cells, the cells nearly equal in length, second recurrent vein meets distal to second submarginal crossvein (
Fig. 15a
); arolia absent (
Fig. 15a
); metasomal terga without maculations (
Fig. 15e
). Integument black, except one small yellow marking on vertex near apex of eye (
Fig. 15b
, 
Fig. 15d
), reddish-brown on tarsi (
Fig. 15a
). Fore wing hyaline, slightly brownish, veins and stigma dark blackish-brown (
Fig. 15a
). Pubescence on T1–T3 black (
Fig. 15e
), T5–T6 with fox-reddish pubescence (
Fig. 15f
); lower part of face with long black pubescence (
Fig. 15b
); vertex, scutum and scutellum covered with long yellowish-white pubescence (
Fig. 15a
, 
Fig. 15d
); gena, mesepisternum covered long black pubescence; tarsi covered with reddish-brown hair, femora, tibiae covered with long black hair; scopa fox-reddish.
